                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30093/2605.30093v1/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Canonicalized 3D object reconstruction pipeline.Given an image, we obtain an instance mask and a mesh from foundation models. We then refine the mesh pose via a two-phase render-and-compare optimization based on a distance-transform (DT) and a soft-IoU phase. Finally, we resolve the residual four-fold yaw ambiguity by rendering the mesh at eight known orientations and applying OrientAnything V2 with majority voting to select the canonical yaw correctionΔ​ψ∗\\Delta\\psi^{*}.",
                "position": 415
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30093/2605.30093v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:Pseudo-label correspondences pipeline.Given two images, we fuse DINO, SD, and PartField features (rasterized from the meshes ofsection˜3.1) and propose candidate matches via nearest-neighbor (NN) search with relaxed cyclic consistency (c.c). Each candidate is then geometrically verified by lifting the matched pixels onto the reconstructed meshes and computing the geodesic errordgeos⇄td_{\\text{geo}}^{s\\rightleftarrows t}; candidates exceeding thresholdτgeo\\tau_{\\text{geo}}are rejected. The retained pseudo-labels𝒫\\mathcal{P}are used to train a lightweight correspondence adapter on top of frozen DINO+SD features.",
                "position": 522
            }
        ]
